        <p class="article-meta">By Rayan Fiver • 18 Apr 2026 • 10 min read</p>
        <p class="article-intro">
          Good UI design is built on timeless principles. Understanding and applying these fundamentals will dramatically improve the quality of your designs and create more intuitive user experiences.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article-content">
        <h2>Visual Hierarchy</h2>
        <p>
          Visual hierarchy guides users through your interface by establishing what's most important. It's created through strategic use of size, color, contrast, spacing, and typography.
        </p>

        <h3>Implementing Hierarchy</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Use size to emphasize importance</li>
          <li>Apply contrasting colors to draw attention</li>
          <li>Leverage whitespace to isolate elements</li>
          <li>Use typography weight and size strategically</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Contrast and Readability</h2>
        <p>
          Contrast is crucial for both aesthetics and accessibility. Maintain at least 4.5:1 contrast ratio for normal text to ensure readability for everyone, including those with visual impairments.
        </p>

        <h2>Alignment and Spacing</h2>
        <p>
          Consistent alignment creates order and makes interfaces feel polished. Use a spacing scale to maintain visual rhythm throughout your designs.
        </p>

        <h2>Color Psychology</h2>
        <p>
          Colors evoke emotions and influence behavior. Choose a palette that supports your design goals while maintaining accessibility standards.
        </p>

        <h2>Whitespace: The Unsung Hero</h2>
        <p>
          Whitespace reduces cognitive load and helps users focus. It's not wasted space—it's a powerful design tool. Use it strategically to create elegant, readable designs.
        </p>

        <h2>Consistency and Patterns</h2>
        <p>
          Consistency reduces the learning curve. Establish patterns and maintain them throughout your interface. Create design systems to ensure uniformity across all pages.
        </p>

        <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Visual hierarchy guides user attention</li>
          <li>Contrast is essential for accessibility</li>
          <li>Consistency breeds user confidence</li>
          <li>Whitespace is your design ally</li>
          <li>Typography is a powerful design tool</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

